"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670060","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-16","<p>During 2015/16 there were 5 fatalities, 52 major injuries and 1,388 minor injuries recorded on the national rail network in passenger incidents at the platform/train interface; information is not recorded on which of these may have involved trains which were driver-only operated or which had a driver and a guard. These represent, respectively, around one fatality in every 350 million journeys, one major injury in every 30 million journeys, and one minor injury in every 1 million journeys.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-16T11:40:42.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670060/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Railway Stations: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many train-platform interface injuries were recorded in the latest year for which figures are available; how many of those were on driver-only operated trains; and what each figure represents as a proportion of relevant passenger journeys.","false","Biography information for Lord Lucas",,"Lord Lucas","HL4418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670061","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>A revised version of the Ministerial Code was published on the 21<sup>st</sup> December 2016, which removed the provisions for setting up Extended Ministerial Offices (EMOs). My officials are working with the Civil Service Commission and relevant departments on the process of disbanding any remaining EMOs.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-12T09:06:59.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670061/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670061/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-09","Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many current Ministers have been allocated an extended ministerial office (EMO); how many staff work in each EMO; how many of those staff were civil servants prior to moving to the EMO; how many of those staff have been recruited from outside the civil service; and what the salary grade is of those EMO staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670062","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>The statistics provided in the Written Answer from the Minister of State for School Standards on 20 October 2016 (HC47083) show that around 90% of qualified teachers are employed in a state-funded school in the year after qualification (and this has been the case since 1996). Of the qualified teachers who started teaching in 2010, 70% were still teaching in a state-funded school five years later.</p><p> </p><p>These teacher retention statistics only cover qualified teachers, that is teachers who have successfully completed an accredited programme of training or assessment and have been awarded Qualified Teacher Status (QTS). Statistics on teacher retention by length of time in post are not available by school phase nor by the route through which the teacher trained.</p><p> </p><p>The published teacher retention statistics are in Tables 7 and 8 of the ‘School Workforce in England: November 2015’ statistical release.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-18T13:46:35.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670062/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670062/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Teachers: Resignations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Nick Gibb MP on 20 October 2016 (HC47083), what proportion of the state school teachers who have left the profession within five years of starting in 2010 were (1) professionally trained, and (2) 1-year post-graduate PGCE trained; and what proportion of those come from (a) the primary sector; and (b) the post-primary sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL4419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670063","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Departments publish annual information on their spend on non-consolidated performance related pay on their own websites. This information can be found on <a href="http://data.gov.uk/" target="_blank">data.gov.uk</a>. The latest set of this information was published in March 2016 and relates to the 2014/15 performance year.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-12T09:03:04.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670063/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670063/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-09","Civil Servants: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much each Government Department has paid in bonuses to civil servants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670064","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>There are more than 456,000 teachers in state-funded schools throughout England – up more than 15,000 since 2010. The retention rate for new teachers is around 90% and of those that started in 2010, 70% are still in the classroom.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s Teacher Supply Model estimates the number of new teachers we need to train each year. Based on the National Audit Office Report on “Training new teachers”, it cost £700 million to train 33,200 trainees in 2013/14. This report is attached.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-17T16:16:59.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670064/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670064/answer","HL4420 Attachment.pdf","HL4420 Attachment.pdf","HL_4420_Attachment","HL_4420_Attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670064/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Teachers: Resignations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the ongoing annual additional cost of state school teachers leaving the profession within five years of starting in 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL4420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670065","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Government has no plans to conduct an investigation into the collapse of Bradford and Bingley plc in 2008.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office concluded in its report of 4 December 2009 that the public support provided to the UK’s banking system by the Treasury was justified, given the scale of both the economic and social costs if one or more major banks had collapsed. In providing that support, the Treasury met two of the Government’s principal objectives, namely maintaining financial stability and protecting retail depositors.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-12T14:31:21.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670065/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Bradford and Bingley","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will investigate the collapse of Bradford and Bingley plc in 2008.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","59051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670066","Department for Education","false","2017-01-16","<p>The department makes no assessment of the comparative demand for specific types of school places. Local authorities (LAs) have a statutory responsibility to ensure there are sufficient school places for their areas and they will take parental demand into account when deciding where additional places are needed. Where there is specific demand for additional Catholic school places, it is for the LA to decide how best to meet that demand. This could be through establishing a new school or expanding an existing school.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-16T13:29:22.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670066/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670066/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Church Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the comparative demand between regions from parents for places in Catholic schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670067","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Valuation Office Agency (VOA) aims to respond to correspondence from Members within 15 working days of receipt, however certain cases may take longer. The VOA apologises for the delay in responding to the correspondence while they investigated the issues raised in the letter. The Chief Executive has sent a reply.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-12T13:48:09.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670067/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the hon. Member for Walsall North will receive a reply to his letter of 28 November 2016 to the Chief Executive of the Valuation Office Agency, ref 11780517.1/CEO; and what the reasons are for the delay in responding to that letter.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","59040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670068","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>As set out in our recent White Paper on Prison Safety and Reform, we are committed to giving prisoners the support and help they need to maintain and strengthen family ties.</p><p> </p><p>Lord Farmer, working in partnership with Clinks, has been commissioned to investigate how supporting men in prison to engage with their families can help reduce reoffending and assist in addressing intergenerational crime. He is expected to report this Spring.</p><p> </p><p>From this Autumn 2017, we will devolve the family service budgets to governors so that they have flexibility over how to spend it. In advance of that, we are re-procuring contracts so that governors have maximum flexibility and discretion to put in place the services that would best meet the needs of their prisoners. We are also reviewing best practice in existing service provision, including provision of family days and other family learning activities.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-23T12:14:49.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670068/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670068/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisoners: Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to improve support available to children and families of prisoners.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670069","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The White Paper <em>Prison Safety and Reform</em> described the steps the Government has already taken to strip out unnecessary rules and governance from prison education contracts to allow governors more oversight and control. The document committed to implementing a number of recommendations from Dame Sally Coates’ review, and said that further plans will be set out in a detailed education strategy to be published later this year.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-23T12:15:29.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670069/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670069/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prison Education Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps have they taken to implement the recommendations of Dame Sally Coates’ review of education in prisons <i>Unlocking Potential: A review of education in prisons.</i>","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670070","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Prison Service is committed to enabling prisoners to practice their religion, and all prisons have multi faith chaplaincy teams to enable and facilitate this. Instructions and guidance on religious practice in prisons is set out in PSI 5/2016 (Faith and Pastoral Care for Prisoners).</p><p> </p><p>Formal assurance visits (which include a focus group with prisoners) are made to each prison regularly by a member of the Chaplaincy HQ team to assure the Governor/Director and Head of Chaplaincy of compliance with the PSI. In this way, and through the use of the application system by which prisoners can request to see a Chaplain, any issues or barriers can be identified in a systematic way by local prison management and HQ. The Head of Chaplaincy meets regularly with Faith Advisers for the National Offender Management Service, as well as faith based organisations.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4425","2017-01-24T16:46:39.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670070/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670070/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisons: Religious Practice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they are working with prison chaplains and faith groups to protect prisoners’ right to practise their faith.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670071","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Prison Service is committed to enabling prisoners to practice their religion, and all prisons have multi faith chaplaincy teams to enable and facilitate this. Instructions and guidance on religious practice in prisons is set out in PSI 5/2016 (Faith and Pastoral Care for Prisoners).</p><p> </p><p>Formal assurance visits (which include a focus group with prisoners) are made to each prison regularly by a member of the Chaplaincy HQ team to assure the Governor/Director and Head of Chaplaincy of compliance with the PSI. In this way, and through the use of the application system by which prisoners can request to see a Chaplain, any issues or barriers can be identified in a systematic way by local prison management and HQ. The Head of Chaplaincy meets regularly with Faith Advisers for the National Offender Management Service, as well as faith based organisations.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4424","2017-01-24T16:46:39.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670071/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670071/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisons: Ministers of Religion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the barriers to accessing chaplaincy in prisons.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670072","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>The review is considering the training provided by public institutions to faith leaders of all faiths working in the prison service, health service, schools and higher and further education. The review is not examining the theological content of religious teaching.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-23T16:31:25.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670072/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670072/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Counter-terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they will define structured training in relation to their review of training for faith leaders in public institutions in the Counter-Extremism Strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Murphy of Torfaen",,"Lord Murphy of Torfaen","HL4426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670073","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-23","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government. The FCA does not comment on individual firms.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is currently carrying out a post-implementation review into their crowdfunding rules and published a statement before Christmas with their latest update on this. Peer-to-Peer lenders are also currently going through the FCA authorisations process, whereby the FCA will assess their business models against the threshold conditions. Where a firm does not meet FCA statutory standards they will not be authorised.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-23T15:39:59.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670073/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Wellesley and Co","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have reviewed the solvency of peer-to-peer lender Wellesley &amp; Co. and the conduct of the firm's principals and owners.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL4427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670074","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-23","<p>We are in the process of considering the findings of the pilot programmes. Once we have concluded that consideration, we will decide how best to respond.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-01-23T15:04:49.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670074/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670074/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-09","Local Government: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 19 December 2016 (HL3833), whether they plan to publish a formal written response to the findings of the local pilot programmes on statutory notices.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL4428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670075","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The BBC Board as a whole is required by the Royal Charter to ensure that the BBC promotes all of its Public Purposes, including helping people from all parts of the UK to understand and engage with the world around them. The Charter also sets out that there must be a 'Nation Member' for each of the UK’s four constituent nations who will have a specific role in ensuring that the BBC is both engaging with and reflecting all regions and diverse communities of the whole of the UK. Representatives from local government are eligible to apply for any of the roles on the Board which are currently being advertised.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-01-19T11:42:26.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670075/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670075/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-09","BBC Board","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 5 December 2016 (HL3691), whether a representative from local government will be eligible to join the new BBC Board in order to help ensure that the BBC meets its public purpose of helping audiences to engage fully with major regional and local issues.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL4429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670076","Department for Education","false","2017-01-20","<p>The government knows how important swift access to defibrillators can be in cases of cardiac arrest. That is why we are encouraging schools to purchase a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment. To help enable schools to do so, the Department for Education have negotiated a deal with NHS Supply Chain to offer defibrillators to schools at a reduced cost, and have published advice on installing and maintaining defibrillators on school premises.</p><p> </p><p>Since this scheme was launched in 2014, over 1800 schools have purchased defibrillators through this route. We continue to work with the sector to raise awareness of the scheme and to refine our guidance to schools on installing and maintaining these devices.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Chancellor announced in the budget in March that the government is making available another £1 million to make public access defibrillators and coronary pulmonary resuscitation training more widely available in communities across England. This builds on last year’s funding of £1 million, which provided almost 700 more publicly accessible defibrillators in communities across England and increased the numbers of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-20T13:23:24.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670076/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670076/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Public Buildings: Defibrillators","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that each school and public building has an accessible defibrillator.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670077","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-17","<p>Tackling the very high rate of maternal deaths and teenage pregnancy is a priority for DFID’s work in Sierra Leone, and the Aberdeen Women’s Centre is providing critical services to many women and girls. DFID is supporting them and other birth centres by providing free life-saving medicines.</p><p>The Secretary of State visited the Centre in November to see the work they are doing and on Monday the 9th January Minister Wharton met this week with The Gloag Foundation, who provide funding for the Centre, to discuss potential areas of collaboration in achieving our shared goals.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-17T17:35:32.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670077/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670077/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Sierra Leone: Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to support and promote, as a centre of excellence, the Aberdeen Women’s Hospital in Sierra Leone.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670078","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:49:35.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670078/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Treasury: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many members of staff who ceased to be employed by his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years have subsequently been re-employed by his Department on a temporary basis or as a third-party contractor or consultant.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","59177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670079","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-17","<p>We welcome this year’s national voluntary reviews which provided an opportunity to learn from other countries’ approaches to delivering the Global Goals for Sustainable Development. The Government will put itself forward for review in due course and will decide the exact process thereafter.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-17T17:37:08.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670079/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670079/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have an action plan for the voluntary national review under the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670080","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-12","<p>The issue with some Volkswagen diesel cars refers to their nitrogen dioxide emissions. Vehicle Excise Duty bands are set according to carbon dioxide emissions, which are not affected by the existence of “defeat devices”.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-12T13:51:04.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670080/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670080/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Question 58110, whether his Department has modelled which VED bands the 1.2 million affected VW vehicles would have been placed in had the correct emissions data been available at the time of registration.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670081","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government is considering the best timing for putting itself forward for a voluntary national review at the UN High Level Political Forum. We welcome this year’s reviews which provided an opportunity to learn from other countries’ approaches to delivering the Global Goals for Sustainable Development.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-16T15:05:21.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670081/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670081/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will conduct the voluntary national review relating to the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670082","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Chief Secretaries to the Treasury regularly discuss matters of mutual interest, including annual fiscal events, with Northern Ireland Finance Ministers. However, no such discussions took place on the costs of Northern Ireland renewable heating schemes, including in the context of the settlement letter which followed the 2015 Spending Review and Autumn Statement.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T12:55:44.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670082/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions the then Chief Secretary to the Treasury had with Ministers of the Northern Ireland Executive on (a) the Autumn Statement 2015 and (b) his subsequent Settlement Letter referring to the costs of Northern Ireland's non-domestic renewable heat incentive scheme.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","59200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670083","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Global Goals for Sustainable Development have been integrated into departments Single Departmental Plans. The Government will put itself forward for voluntary national review in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-17T17:36:11.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670083/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670083/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which government departments will be responsible for the voluntary national review relating to the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670084","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Treasury ministers did not discuss the Renewable Heat Incentive scheme with Ministers of the Northern Ireland Executive in 2015. The Treasury’s role is to set a budget allocation for renewable heat schemes in Northern Ireland proportionate to the budget provided to the department which manages similar schemes in Great Britain. It is for the Executive to meet any costs in excess of that budget from its block grant or the other resources available to it.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-17T12:54:46.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670084/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670084/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether discussions between Ministers of his Department and Ministers of the Northern Ireland Executive on budgetary challenges facing the Executive during 2015 included the escalated spending exposure under the Northern Ireland non-domestic renewable heat incentive scheme.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","59192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670085","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Sustainable Development Goals have been integrated into relevant Departments’ Single Departmental Plans. Departments will report against progress towards the Goals through their Annual Reports and Accounts.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-16T15:06:13.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670085/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670085/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what processes they will use in developing the national reports relating to the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670086","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The number of departmental staff who are in the redeployment pool are fewer than five. It is the Treasury's policy for reasons of confidentiality not to release full details relating to numbers of staff fewer than five, where to do so might lead to the identification of individual cases.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:52:50.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670086/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670086/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Treasury: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670087","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Government will put itself forward for voluntary national review in due course and will decide the exact process, including Whitehall coordination thereafter.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-17T17:36:29.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670087/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670087/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have a cross-Whitehall coordinator for the voluntary national review relating to the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670088","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Money Purchase Annual Allowance applies to anyone who has accessed their pension savings flexibly and makes further money purchase savings. It applies at the level in force at the time of making those subsequent savings.</p><p>The Government has proposed a reduction in the allowance to £4,000 from 6 April 2017 and launched a consultation on the detail surrounding this, which ends on 15 February and is available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reducing-the-money-purchase-annual-allowance</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-17T17:17:00.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670088/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670088/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the reduction to £4,000 in the Money Purchase Annual Allowance referred to in paragraph 4.20 of the Autumn Statement 2016, Cm 9362, will apply to people who had already accessed their savings flexibly.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","59110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670089","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>I am sorry but the Home Office does not hold the specific information in the format requested.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-23T16:39:52.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670089/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670089/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many successful applicants for Tier 1 (Investor) visas, between 2008 and 2015 inclusive, have been classified then or since as politically-exposed persons.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL4437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670090","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>Information on the numbers of grants, refusals, withdrawals and lapsed cases for Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1), available from the GOV.UK website and attached to this answer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-23T17:55:39.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670090/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670090/answer","Entry Clearance Visa Apps.xls","Entry Clearance Visa Apps.xls","Entry Clearance Visa Applications","Entry Clearance Visa Applications","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670090/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications were rejected between 2008 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL4438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670091","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Prior to announcing proposals for a secondary market in annuities, the Government consulted a broad evidence base to understand how this market might operate. This includes modelling estimates of how many annuity holders might sell their annuity, and a consideration of the views expressed by annuity providers and other potential market participants.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:45:27.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670091/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670091/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department made of the viability of the secondary annuities market, before its announcement of a scheme to enable pensioners to sell their annuities.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","59247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670092","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>Information on the numbers of grants, refusals, withdrawals and lapsed cases for Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1), available from the GOV.UK website and attached to this answer.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-23T17:55:59.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670092/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670092/answer","Entry Clearance Visa Apps.xls","Entry Clearance Visa Apps.xls","Entry Clearance Visa Applications","Entry Clearance Visa Applications","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670092/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications have been rejected since the tightening of conditions for acceptance in 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL4439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670093","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>Following the Chancellor’s announcement of pension freedoms at Budget 2014, several organisations contacted the Government to suggest ways these flexibilities could be extended to existing annuity holders. These suggestions led to HM Treasury having discussions with a range of potential market participants, including annuity providers, about the prospect of a secondary market in annuities. These discussions culminated in the announcement at March Budget 2015 that the Government would create the conditions to allow a secondary market in annuities to develop.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout the development of the policy the Government continued to engage extensively with the pensions and investment industry, consumer groups and financial regulators on how to create a competitive secondary market in annuities.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:44:28.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670093/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670093/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department had with representatives of the annuities industry before taking the decision to (a) allow the sale of annuities and (b) revoke that policy; and when did such discussions take place.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","59248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670094","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>I am sorry but the Home Office does not hold the specific information in the format requested. To obtain it would involve interrogating individual case records, incurring disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-23T16:10:12.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670094/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670094/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many residence permits granted to Tier 1 (Investor) visa applicants have been rescinded since 2008; and on what grounds.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Saltaire",,"Lord Wallace of Saltaire","HL4440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670095","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-17","<p>In April 2015, the Government introduced the pension freedoms to give individuals greater flexibility in how they access their pension savings (from the age of 55) by removing the obligation for people to buy an annuity upon retirement. However, these flexibilities did not apply to those individuals who had already purchased an annuity.</p><p> </p><p>In order to extend the flexibilities to these individuals, at the March Budget 2015 the Government announced its intention to remove the restrictions on the sale of existing annuities and to create the conditions for a secondary market in annuities to develop. The Government expected that for most people continuing to hold their annuity would be the right decision, but wanted to give people choice over how they use their money.</p><p> </p><p>However, as the policy developed it became increasingly clear that consumers would have received poor value for their income streams and the conditions to allow a vibrant and competitive market to emerge, with multiple buyers and sellers of annuities, could not be created with sufficient consumer protections. In these circumstances the Government concluded that it would not be in consumers’ interests to continue with this policy. The Government announced in October 2016 that it would no longer be continuing with proposals for a secondary market in annuities.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-17T14:47:39.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670095/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670095/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-09","Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on enabling pensioners who were obliged to buy annuities to transfer their investment into alternative financial vehicles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","59249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670096","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>The information requested is publicly available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department collects information on all school staff employed by state funded schools each year in the November School Workforce Census. The results of each census are published annually. The latest information is for November 2015 and was published in June 2016 in the ‘School Workforce in England: November 2015’ statistical release. This is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Time series statistics (2005 to 2015) showing the number of full-time equivalent teachers, teaching assistants, and other school staff working in primary, secondary and special schools are published in Table 1 of the above statistical release.</p><p> </p><p>Table 3a of the release shows the number of full-time equivalent teachers working in local authority maintained schools and separately in academy and free schools in the primary, secondary and special school phases. Similar information for the number of full-time equivalent teaching assistants, and other school staff working in local authority maintained schools and separately in academy and free schools is available in Table 3b.</p><p> </p><p>The detailed breakdown of the full-time equivalent staffing numbers in 2014 (shown separately for local authority maintained schools and academy and free schools) is available in Tables 1-3 of the previous year’s statistical release. This is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2014</a></p>",,"Lord Nash","HL4442 ; HL4443 ; HL4444 ; HL4445","2017-01-17T15:22:30.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670096/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670096/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Schools: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many support staff, expressed as full-time equivalents, were employed in English primary, secondary and special state schools, in (1) 2007–8, (2) 2011–12, and (3) 2015–16, or if 2015–16 data are not yet available, 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL4441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670097","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-12","<p>The £140million Estate Regeneration Fund was launched on 8 December 2016 alongside the publication of the Estate Regeneration National Strategy. Following extensive engagement with over 120 schemes around the country, an additional £32m of enabling and capacity building grant was made available.</p><p>Initial registrations for the £140m recoverable investment funding have already been received and funding allocations will be announced when the assessment process is completed.</p><p>Allocations for the £32m grant funding will be made in the current financial year.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-12T17:13:54.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670097/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670097/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-09","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 8 March 2016 to Question 29619, how much of the £140 million fund relating to the redevelopment of 100 sink estates has been allocated to date.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670098","Department for Education","false","2017-01-17","<p>The information requested is publicly available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department collects information on all school staff employed by state funded schools each year in the November School Workforce Census. The results of each census are published annually. The latest information is for November 2015 and was published in June 2016 in the ‘School Workforce in England: November 2015’ statistical release. This is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Time series statistics (2005 to 2015) showing the number of full-time equivalent teachers, teaching assistants, and other school staff working in primary, secondary and special schools are published in Table 1 of the above statistical release.</p><p> </p><p>Table 3a of the release shows the number of full-time equivalent teachers working in local authority maintained schools and separately in academy and free schools in the primary, secondary and special school phases. Similar information for the number of full-time equivalent teaching assistants, and other school staff working in local authority maintained schools and separately in academy and free schools is available in Table 3b.</p><p> </p><p>The detailed breakdown of the full-time equivalent staffing numbers in 2014 (shown separately for local authority maintained schools and academy and free schools) is available in Tables 1-3 of the previous year’s statistical release. This is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2014</a></p>",,"Lord Nash","HL4441 ; HL4443 ; HL4444 ; HL4445","2017-01-17T15:22:30.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670098/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670098/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Schools: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many support staff, expressed as full-time equivalents, employed in English primary, secondary and special state schools, were employed as teaching assistants, learning support assistants or in other primarily classroom-based roles, in (1) 2007–8, (2) 2011–12, and (3) 2015–16, or if 2015–16 data are not yet available, 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL4442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670099","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Fair Funding Review is conducting a thorough review of what the relative needs assessment formula for local councils should be in a world in which local government spending is funded by local resources not central grant and will set the baselines for 100% Business Rates Retention system. One of the key areas of work for the review is to look at the available evidence about what factors drive the costs local councils face. The Review is considering a number of factors including how to take into account changes in local populations.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-16T17:06:21.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670099/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670099/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670099/answer/previousversion/29609","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-09","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the recommendations set out in the Casey Review, if he will ensure that changes in the level of immigration are taken into account in the forthcoming fair funding review on local government finance.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","59162"
