"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670291","Home Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Home Office does not have access to non-departmental public bodies' data and is unable to provide the answer to this part of the question.</p><p>There were 26 members of staff previously employed as permanent civil servants who left the Department during the 3 years from 1 December 2013 to 30 November 2016 and were recorded as re-employed as an agency worker or contractor during this period.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-12T12:48:00.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670291/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670291/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Home Office: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many members of staff who ceased to be employed by her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years have subsequently been re-employed by her Department on a temporary basis or as a third-party contractor or consultant.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","59175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670292","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Home Office has a rigorous governance process in place for all required goods and services. Suppliers are subject to robust due diligence during the well established, transparent and fair procurement process. Following procurement, every provider commissioned by the Home Office is held accountable via contractual compliance arrangements. Strategic suppliers such as G4S are actively managed across Government and are subject to internal and external governance protocols.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-19T13:37:27.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670292/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670292/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","G4S","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications for her Department's policies of the report by Liberty entitled G4S: a history of discrimination, human rights violations, malpractice and mismanagement in the UK, published in 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","59243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670293","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>UK support contributed to a halving of global malaria death rates since 2000. DFID continues to be a global leader in malaria control. UK aid is saving lives around the world, including through our support to the Global Fund (our replenishment commitment will fund 40 million bednets), UNITAID (to increase access to new diagnostics and medicines), research to accelerate the development of drugs, diagnostics and insecticides, and helping countries scale up their own national malaria control programmes.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-16T14:32:34.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670293/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670293/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Malaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of its January 2016 pledge to spend up to £500 million a year on tackling malaria.","false","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","59225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670294","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>My Department does have a redeployment pool at present. Staff are placed in redeployment as they are in a formal redundancy consultation process. The current number in this group is three.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-16T17:57:46.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670294/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670294/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Department for International Development: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many civil servants in each unit of her Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670295","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK has communicated its support for Italy’s plans to host a nutrition event in 2017 as part of its G7 Presidency.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-16T14:31:57.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670295/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670295/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that nutrition is prioritised on the UK's G7 agenda.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","59130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670296","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government has committed to improve the nutrition of 50 million people in developing countries by 2020. We will particularly focus on preventing and treating undernutrition among infants and young children. We will also equip governments in the Scaling Up Nutrition Movement to sustain improvements in the nutrition of children in their own countries.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-16T14:31:35.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670296/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670296/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to tackle under-nutrition in infants and young children in high-burden countries.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","59127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670297","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-16","<p>DFID monitors all its nutrition programmes in low and middle income countries on an annual basis. For example, DFID’s programme in northern Nigeria aims to reduce stunting and wasting by at least 4% over 7 years and includes investment with partners to monitor impact. DFID is also building the capacity of governments to collect and use nutrition data effectively. DFID supports the Global Nutrition Report which tracks progress to reduce undernutrition globally.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-16T14:31:01.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670297/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670297/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Developing Countries: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to monitor the impact of UK Government nutrition investments and programmes in low and middle-income countries.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","59126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670298","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-17","<p>DFID spends aid through a range of delivery partners. Delivery partners are selected based on a value for money assessment of their capacity to deliver objectives in the country DFID is working in.</p><p>Overall, for 2015, approximately 36% of DFID’s aid was delivered through multilateral organisations, 64% was delivered bilaterally.</p><p>Details of 2015 spend on all UK official aid is published in the Statistics on International Development, including the delivery channels used in every country in which we work.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-17T18:00:46.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670298/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670298/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-09","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's aid budget is given to third parties to distribute.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","59070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670299","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-15","<p>English law has had a huge impact, spreading the rule of law around the world. It is the law of choice in over a quarter of jurisdictions. We will be championing our £25 billion legal services industry as a key part of post-Brexit global Britain.</p><p> </p><p>We are not aware of any reports that include aggregate data on the contribution that international, including EU, firms make to the UK economy. It may also be the case that firms do not separate out their UK income from their wider income, especially where they operate in a number of jurisdictions, or where work is spread across jurisdictions or provided across borders.</p><p> </p><p>English common law is the preferred choice for international commercial contracts, and English law governs about 40 per cent of all global corporate arbitrations.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-15T10:05:08.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670299/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670299/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate her Department has made of the financial contribution to the UK economy of law firms based elsewhere in the EU and operating in the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670300","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-12","Education is key to helping prisoners turn their lives around and in particular to securing employment which we know reduces the likelihood of reoffending. Alongside introducing a core common curriculum, focussing on maths and English, we will empower Governors to put in place a framework of incentives to encourage participation by those prisoners with poor literacy skills.","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-12T17:54:05.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670300/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670300/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisoners: Literacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will introduce compulsory literacy classes for prisoners assessed as having poor literacy.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","59095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670301","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The wastage rate of staff employed by the Legal Aid Agency is shown below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Twelve months to:</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Wastage rate</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-14</p></td><td><p>6.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-15</p></td><td><p>4.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31-Mar-16</p></td><td><p>4.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>30-Sep-16</p></td><td><p>4.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T14:53:21.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670301/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670301/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Legal Aid Agency: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the wastage rate of staff employed by the Legal Aid Agency in each year since that agency's creation on 1 April 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","59046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670302","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-12","The range of £3 to £10 which formed part of the call for evidence section of the consultation document was based on figures from a variety of reports and investigations carried out by the Office of Fair Trading, the Competition Commission, the Competition and Markets Authority and from industry sources.","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-12T17:50:03.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670302/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670302/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 130 of her Department's consultation entitled, Reforming the Soft Tissue Injury Claims Process, published in November 2016, what the evidential basis is for the assertion that credit hire costs added up to £10 per policy to car insurance premiums.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","59029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670303","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>All Independent Monitoring Board annual reports for prisons are responded to by Ministers. Those responses set out what has or will be done to address issues identified by Boards. I wrote to the Chair of the Birmingham Board on 28 November 2016 in response to the concerns raised in their report.</p><p> </p><p>The long-standing challenges in our prison estate cannot be fixed overnight but the Justice Secretary and I are absolutely committed to making prisons places of safety and reform. We already embarking on a major recruitment drive to boost the frontline with 2,500 extra prison officers and are putting in place new security measures to tackle drones, phones and drugs, which undermine safety.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","59015","2017-01-23T11:14:11.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670303/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670303/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she has taken to implement the IMB Annual Reports on prisons in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","59018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670304","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>All Independent Monitoring Board annual reports for prisons are responded to by Ministers. Those responses set out what has or will be done to address issues identified by Boards. I wrote to the Chair of the Birmingham Board on 28 November 2016 in response to the concerns raised in their report.</p><p> </p><p>The long-standing challenges in our prison estate cannot be fixed overnight but the Justice Secretary and I are absolutely committed to making prisons places of safety and reform. We already embarking on a major recruitment drive to boost the frontline with 2,500 extra prison officers and are putting in place new security measures to tackle drones, phones and drugs, which undermine safety.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","59018","2017-01-23T11:14:11.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670304/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670304/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Birmingham Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she has taken to implement the most recent IMB Annual Report on HM Prison Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","59015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670305","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The number of offenders who have had their Community Order or Suspended Sentence Order revoked as a result of failure to comply or committing a further offence is monitored under the Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) contract. Underperformance against this measure can result in a Service Credit being applied. As detailed in the response to Question 54906, if a CRC fails to meet the required performance measure, we can require the CRC to pay a Service Credit to recompense for the minimum level of loss or damage as a result of a reduced provision of services. The application of Service Credits is a standard part of our contract management process.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, orders revoked as a result of reoffending may impact payments under contracted Payment by Results incentives.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-23T11:10:36.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670305/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670305/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2016 to Question 54906, whether payments to a community rehabilitation company are reduced when an offender is returned to court having (a) committed a further offence or (b) failed to comply with a community order.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","59010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670306","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-12","<p>NOMS takes the issue of violence against staff very seriously. It currently has systems in place to deal with perpetrators quickly and robustly, with serious incidents referred to the police for prosecution. It is working closely with the police and CPS to develop a new joint protocol to report crimes in prison, this includes pushing for prosecutions when prison staff are attacked.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS does not currently publish sickness absence rates for prison officers, but these will be published for the first time in the NOMS Workforce Bulletin on 16 February 2017. This data will include data on approved claims for sick leave excusal, whereby a period of absence that can be attributed to an assault at work does not count against the officer's allowance of sick pay.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-12T18:00:02.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670306/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670306/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prison Officers: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what number of days of sick leave have been recorded by prison officers in each year since 2010; and what number of those were as a consequence of violence within prisons.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","59096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670307","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The National Offender Management Service’s new Instruction ‘The Care and Management of Transgender Offenders’, published on 9 November 2016, drew on the conclusions of the Ministry of Justice Review of transgender offenders. It both replaced the earlier Prison Service Instruction and extended its scope to include transgender offenders in the community. The new Instruction was fully implemented on 1 January 2017, following a transitional period of operation. Staff are being supported in the implementation of the new arrangements through guidance and training.</p><p> </p><p>Our top priority is the welfare of those in our custody and following a thorough review, we have taken action to improve the way we manage and support transgender offenders.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to making prisons places of safety and reform and have invested in specialist mental health training for prison officers as well as launching a suicide and self-harm reduction project.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-23T12:07:30.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670307/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670307/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisoners: Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress her Department has made on implementing the recommendations of the review on the care and management of transgender offenders, published in November 2016 on the safeguarding of transgender prisoners on the prison estate.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","59161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670308","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-19","<p>Leaving rates of prison staff, broken down by grade are included in the NOMS Workforce Bulletin which are published quarterly on gov.uk</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-19T13:59:58.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670308/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670308/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prison Service: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the wastage rates of public sector prison support staff in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","59169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670309","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>My department does have a redeployment pool at present as we are in the process of a restructure. Staff are placed in redeployment as they are in a formal redundancy consultation process. The current number in this group is 122.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone in a redeployment pool undertakes meaningful work in support of key departmental priorities and must perform to the same standard as those in permanent roles.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T11:50:26.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670309/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670309/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Ministry of Justice: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many civil servants in each unit of her Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670310","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>Reliable information on post-conviction remand status for offenders convicted at Crown courts is not centrally held and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","59221","2017-01-23T12:44:39.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670310/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670310/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of offenders were released from Crown courts on post-conviction bail for the offences of (a) murder, (b) rape, (c) manslaughter, (d) attempted murder and (e) child sex abuse in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","59222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670311","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-16","<p>The MoJ has not made such an assessment. Our work to improve resettlement of prisoners after release is to prioritise finding accommodation and employment and building a life free from crime.</p><p>We are carrying out a comprehensive review of the probation service to improve outcomes for offenders and communities. Public protection is our top priority and we will not hesitate to take the necessary action to make sure our vital reforms are being delivered to reduce reoffending, cut crime and prevent future victims.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-16T10:50:04.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670311/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670311/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Prisoners' Release: Birth Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of making the presentation of birth certificates compulsory for UK-born residents leaving prison to help ensure that they have adequate ID for accessing benefits and other services.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","59224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670312","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>Reliable information on post-conviction remand status for offenders convicted at Crown courts is not centrally held and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","59222","2017-01-23T12:44:39.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670312/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670312/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders of which offence type released from Crown courts on post-conviction bail subsequently failed to surrender for sentencing in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","59221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670313","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-25","<p>The MoJ set the quality threshold in line with Public Procurement Regulations (December 2015). The score required to reach that threshold and proceed to the final stage of evaluation was 80.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-01-25T16:48:36.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670313/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670313/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Ministry of Justice: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2016 to Question 57404, on Ministry of Justice: translation services, which authority sets the quality threshold; and what score is required to reach that threshold.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","59198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670314","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Ministers and officials of the Northern Ireland Office engage regularly with the Executive to discuss matters of mutual interest. However, I am not aware of any specific discussions on the costs of the Northern Ireland renewable heating scheme during the period in question.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-01-16T15:50:31.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670314/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670314/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-09","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether discussions between Ministers or officials of his Department and the Northern Ireland Executive on budgetary challenges facing that Executive during 2015 included the escalated spending exposure under the Northern Ireland non-domestic Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","59190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670315","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Ministers and officials of the Northern Ireland Office engage regularly with HM Treasury to discuss matters of mutual interest in relation to Northern Ireland. However, I am not aware of any specific discussions on the costs of the Northern Ireland renewable heating scheme during the period in question.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-01-16T15:53:40.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670315/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670315/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-09","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the discussions between Ministers and officials of his Department and HM Treasury on budgetary challenges facing the Northern Ireland Executive during 2015 included the escalated spending exposure under the Northern Ireland non-domestic Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","59191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670316","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>No civil servants in the Department are in a redeployment pool.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-01-12T13:00:29.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670316/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670316/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-09","Northern Ireland Office: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670317","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not hold this information.</p><p>Operational matters relating to the Historical Enquiries Team and the Legacy Investigations Branch are the responsibility of the Chief Constable of the Police Service of Northern Ireland.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","59031","2017-01-12T17:50:22.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670317/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670317/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-09","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many former non-state actors who were formerly paramilitaries have been charged following a referral by the Northern Ireland Historical Enquiries Team to the Police Service of Northern Ireland or Public Prosecution Service.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","59030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670318","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not hold this information.</p><p>Operational matters relating to the Historical Enquiries Team and the Legacy Investigations Branch are the responsibility of the Chief Constable of the Police Service of Northern Ireland.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","59030","2017-01-12T17:50:22.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670318/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670318/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-09","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many (a) current and (b) former members of the Armed Forces currently under investigation by the Police Service of Northern Ireland's Legacy Investigations Branch were previously informed by the Northern Ireland Historical Enquiries Team that there would be no further action against them.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","59031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670319","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p>The redeployment pool in the Cabinet Office ceased to exist in 2012 so there are no civil servants in a redeployment pool in this Department.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","59138","2017-01-16T10:33:57.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670319/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670319/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-09","Prime Minister: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants in each unit of 10 Downing Street are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670320","Department of Health","false","2017-01-12","<p>The difference between the published spend and the £11.7 billion estimate is that the published spend relates to clinical commissioning groups only. The £11.7 billion includes mental health spend in specialised commissioning as well as mental health spend on other direct commissioning. NHS England does not report spend on mental health in other direct commissioning.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-12T16:17:01.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670320/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670320/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-09","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2016 to Question 56695 and with reference to the press release issued by the Prime Minister on 8 January 2017, what the reasons are for the discrepancy between the estimated £11.7 billion figure that release said was being spent on mental health and the estimates for such spending derived from the Mental Health Dashboard.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","59218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670321","Department for Education","false","2017-01-12","<p>Children and young people’s mental health and wellbeing is a priority for this Government, as the Prime Minister highlighted in her annual Charity Commission lecture which she delivered on 9 January.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister announced an extension of the Single Point of Contact joint training pilot and a new peer support pilot. We will look to see how we can specifically ensure that Further Education colleges are engaged.</p><p> </p><p>We have already agreed to work with the Association of Colleges in order to share good practice examples of work being undertaken to support the mental health of students.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we will continue to work with the further education sector as a whole as we develop the children and young people’s green paper.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-12T08:47:50.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670321/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670321/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-09","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to announce measures for further education as part of her reforms to young people's mental health.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","59211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670322","Scotland Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Scotland Office has no staff in the redeployment pool. It should be noted that the Scotland Office does not employ staff directly.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-01-12T13:07:53.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670322/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670322/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-09","Scotland Office: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670323","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Department for Transport currently consists of a central Department and four executive agencies. As of the 10<sup>th</sup> January 2017, the following numbers are in the redeployment pool, which is defined as those individuals who are at risk of redundancy.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Agency</p></td><td><p>Number of people</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Central Department</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver Vehicle &amp; Licensing Agency</p></td><td><p>less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency</p></td><td><p>less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle Certification Agency</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver Vehicle &amp; Standards Agency</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-17T09:01:20.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670323/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670323/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Department for Transport: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670324","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-17","<p>A total of 54 members of staff, who have ceased to be employed by the Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years, have returned either on a temporary basis or as a third party contractor or consultant.‎ This number includes those who were originally employed on a fixed term basis.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-17T09:05:25.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670324/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670324/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Department for Transport: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff who ceased to be employed by his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years have subsequently been re-employed by his Department on a temporary basis or as a third-party contractor or consultant.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","59176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670325","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-17","<p>This response only covers England because the Blue Badge scheme is devolved.</p><p> </p><p>There are 2311 Blue Badges on issue to children in England under the age of three who are either dependent upon bulky medical equipment or need to be kept near a vehicle for emergency medical treatment.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold records for children between the ages of two and three who have been issued a Blue Badge under the general walking criterion as this criterion is open to anyone over the age of 2 years. Local authorities would have this data.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-17T14:31:22.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670325/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670325/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Blue Badge Scheme: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many children under the age of three have a blue parking badge in (a) England, (b) Scotland and (c) Wales.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","59049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670326","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-17","<p>The research is due to be completed at the end of 2017 and we expect to publish the findings early next year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-17T14:52:50.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670326/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670326/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Speed Limits: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to publish the findings of research commissioned by his Department into the effects of 20 mph speed zones.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","59048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670327","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The final date for the introduction of the Modern Transport Bill will be announced in due course.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-12T11:09:59.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670327/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670327/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to publish a draft Modern Transport Bill.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","59028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670328","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>HS2 Ltd’s recruitment of a permanent Chief Executive is on track. We expect the successful candidate to be in post this summer subject to any notice periods that may have to be agreed with the individual’s existing employers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T11:15:16.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670328/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670328/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","High Speed Two: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects a permanent Chief Executive at HS2 Ltd to be appointed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","59021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670329","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>HS2 Ltd is in the process of setting up the hotline, which will be in place no later than Royal Assent for Phase One of HS2.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T11:18:25.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670329/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670329/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the MP hotline for HS2 Ltd will be set up and operational.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","59022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670330","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The permanent Construction Commissioner will be appointed by an independent body which will be set up following Royal Assent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T11:22:23.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670330/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670330/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","High Speed Two: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when a permanent High Speed 2 Construction Commissioner will be appointed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","59023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670331","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Road Safety funding is not available until after Royal Assent of the HS2 Bill and, as such no applications have been received. Further details of how this fund will allocated will be announced shortly.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T11:25:33.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670331/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670331/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many applications have been received for High Speed 2 road safety fund monies; and from whom.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","59024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670332","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>Applications for funding for both the Community and Environment Fund and Business and Local Economy Fund will be opened following the Phase One Bill receiving Royal Assent. Both funds will continue to accept applications and award grants for a year following the start of Phase One operations in 2027.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T12:19:17.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670332/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670332/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, over what period of time the High Speed 2 Community and Environment Fund and Business and Local Economy Fund will be available; and when applications for funding will open.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","59025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670333","Wales Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>None.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-01-16T15:39:14.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670333/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670333/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-01-09","Wales Office: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670334","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>DWP does not operate a redeployment pool. Employees whose role is no longer required are managed within their business area and will continue to do meaningful work for the Department. When a new permanent role becomes available, these members of staff will be given priority. Of our 83,332 employees, 23 are currently in this temporary position.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-16T14:54:02.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670334/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670334/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Department for Work and Pensions: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670335","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-17","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. The Carers Credit was introduced in April 2010 and as at January 2017 an estimated 11,500 people were receiving these credits. Over the last five years (January 2012 to December 2016) we estimate that the Carers Credit has been awarded to around 10,000 people.</p><p> </p><p>Source: Department for Work and Pensions Carers Credit Operating System</p><p>Notes: The figure has been rounded to the nearest 100.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-17T15:48:44.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670335/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670335/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","National Insurance Contributions: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have been in receipt of carers credit in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670336","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>We cannot provide this data as it does not meet the quality standard required for official statistics publication</p><p>Statistics on PIP appeals, including the proportion and number of those appeals that were successful, are published online and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a>.</p><p>In addition, breakdowns of PIP reassessment claims by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) are published online at: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Motability is an independent organisation and is responsible for its own management information, including information on its own operating costs.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T17:59:13.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670336/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670336/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Personal Independence Payment: Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, (a) how many personal independence payment (PIP) claimants who lost their entitlement to a Motability vehicle successfully appealed and were awarded a new Motability vehicle, (b) what proportion of PIP claimants whose award was reduced, or who were awarded a lower rate of PIP than they previously received for disability living allowance, so that they were no longer eligible for a Motability vehicle, successfully challenged that decision on appeal and (c) what the cost of supplying new replacement Motability vehicles has been (i) on average per person and (ii) in total over each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","59105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670337","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>Once referred, a claimant will stay on the Work Programme for two years, as long as they continue to claim out of work benefits.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-12T13:51:03.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670337/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670337/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a person starting their own business is required to stay on the Work Programme in order to continue to receive related benefits.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","59103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670338","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-16T14:58:06.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670338/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670338/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Department for Work and Pensions: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many members of staff who ceased to be employed by his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years have subsequently been re-employed by his Department on a temporary basis or as a third-party contractor or consultant.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","59178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670339","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The provisions in the Welfare Reform and Work Act 2016 that repealed the income-related targets set out in the Child Poverty Act 2010 and the associated requirements to publish a child poverty strategy were enacted on 16 March 2016 and came into force on 16 May 2016. As with other machinery of government changes, the policy and analytical functions of the Child Poverty Unit were gradually transferred to the Department for Work and Pensions in line with the planned commencement of the new legislation.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-12T13:55:20.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670339/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670339/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Child Poverty Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57065, on what date was responsibility for child poverty policy and analysis transferred to his Department from the Child Poverty Unit.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","59237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670340","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>We are considering the Supreme Court judgment and what changes are required to comply with its terms, including additional exemptions where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>Claims are assessed by local authorities in line with the Housing Benefit or Universal Credit regulations that apply at the time.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants affected by the Removal of the Spare Room Subsidy policy are able to apply to their local authority for a Discretionary Housing Payment. In the previous Parliament, we significantly increased funding for Discretionary Housing Payments to £470 million and we have already committed a further £870 million in Discretionary Housing Payment funding between 2016/17 and 2020/21.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-12T15:14:55.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670340/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670340/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the implications of its policies of the Supreme Court ruling in November 2016 on the under occupancy penalty; and what estimate he has made of how many people in (a) Southwark and (b) England were incorrectly charged.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","59245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670341","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The numbers of personal independence payment appeals found in favour of the appellant in each year since the benefit was introduced are available in national statistics on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent statistics for the period July to September 2016 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2016</a>.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T12:11:07.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670341/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670341/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-09","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many personal independence payments appeal cases have been successful since the introduction of that benefit.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","59202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670342","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>At Summer Budget 2015, the Chancellor announced a support package of £330m over four years to provide support for people with limited capability for work from April 17. In the Improving Lives, the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper we provided details of this new Personal Support Package.</p><p> </p><p>The £330m additional funding is targeted at new ESA Work Related Activity Group and UC Limited Capability for Work claimants from April 2017 and will deliver a broad range of employment and health support. This will rise from £60m in 2017/18 to £100m in 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the £330m announced at Summer Budget 2015, the 2015 Spending Review announced funding rising to at least £130 million a year by 2019/20 for the new Work and Health Programme. This will provide a new approach which builds on the strengths and lessons learned of current contracted provision including Work Choice and the Work Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The 2017/18 support also consists of a number of trials and proofs of concept to build our evidence base of what works and we will evaluate these measures to build a robust evidence which can inform future years of funding.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T17:34:52.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670342/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670342/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to his oral contribution of 9 January 2017, on health outcomes: work, what the evidential basis is for his statement that his Department will spend an extra £330 million on employment support for employment support allowance claimants compared with current arrangements under the Work Programme and Work Choice.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670343","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The information requested on the number of indvidiuals in receipt of Carer’s Allowance is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the total number of individuals entitled to Carer’s Allowance, including those not in receipt of a payment, is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","59092","2017-01-12T16:00:09.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670343/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670343/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people claiming carer's allowance by age in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670345","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions and his Ministers have not visited a food bank since their appointment.</p><p> </p><p>Secretary of State had a productive meeting with Trussell Trust on 28 November 2016. Jobcentre Plus District Managers have discretion to work with food banks in their own areas if they are invited and if resources are available, as part of their wider community outreach work and we will make sure this continuing advice is communicated appropriately.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-12T13:23:41.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670345/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670345/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which Ministers of his Department have visited a food bank since their appointment; and what the date of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670346","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>DWP has processes in place which enable organisations to provide skills to claimants within Jobcentre Plus. This includes IT/computer skills training which is funded through the Flexible Support Fund. The Universal Credit Programme has made available Universal Support funding to Local Authorities for Assisted Digital Support (ADS).</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-12T13:13:38.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670346/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670346/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Jobcentres: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will take steps to enable organisations to provide computer skills training to claimants within Jobcentre Plus.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","59033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670347","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions offers its apology for the delay in responding. We have been investigating the issues raised in your letter to the Benefit Director on 6 December.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the Department aims to provide a full response to MP enquires on behalf of their constituents within 15 working days, there will be occasions where, for a variety of reasons this is not possible. In this case additional information received from the customer generated further enquiries. Regrettably, the MP's office was not kept informed of progress when it became clear in this particular case there would be a delay. A full response has now been issued to the hon. Member.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T15:45:36.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670347/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670347/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when the hon. Member for Walsall North will receive a reply to his letter to the Benefit Director on 6 December 2016 on employment and support allowance; and what the reasons are for the delay in responding to that letter.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","59039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670348","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Secretary of State holds regular meetings with the Director General, Operations to discuss operational matters and performance. The process of replies being sent to hon. Members has not featured in discussions to date, primarily because the Department’s performance in respect of the timeliness of responses is broadly on track. For the calendar year 2016, 89% of responses to hon. Members were issued within 15 days, against a target of 90% in 15 days. The 90% target reflects the fact that some matters raised by hon. Members can be particularly complex and, in such cases, it is not always possible to respond within 15 days.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T15:55:04.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670348/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670348/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether in his meetings with the Benefits Director he has discussed the process of replies being sent to hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","59041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670350","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The information requested on the number of indvidiuals in receipt of Carer’s Allowance is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the total number of individuals entitled to Carer’s Allowance, including those not in receipt of a payment, is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","59195","2017-01-12T16:00:09.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670350/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670350/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of individuals in receipt of carers allowance in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","59092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670351","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>The available information on sanctions is available at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-12T13:30:47.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670351/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670351/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Social Security Benefits: Cardiff South and Penarth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many individuals were subject to benefit sanctions and for what reason in each of the last 12 months in Cardiff South and Penarth constituency.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","59080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670352","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The ILO unemployment rate was 4.9 per cent in the three months to June 2016 and 4.8 per cent in the three months to September 2016.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-16T14:46:31.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670352/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670352/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-09","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of trends in unemployment since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","59069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670353","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Hendry Review has submitted its report on the strategic case for tidal lagoons to Government. We will now consider the recommendations and determine what is in the best interests of the UK energy consumer and taxpayers in the long term.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:10:41.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670353/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670353/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670353/answer/previousversion/29601","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Tidal Power: Bristol Channel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the viability of proposals for tidal lagoons in the Bristol Channel, including off Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","59079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670354","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-12","<p>Transparency data for Ministers covering the period July to September 2016 was published on Gov.uk on 16<sup>th</sup> December 2016:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-energy-and-industrial-strategy&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-energy-and-industrial-strategy&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-12T14:42:08.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670354/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670354/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish Ministers' transparency details for July to September 2016.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","59083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670355","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>Government policies to support industrial greenhouse gas emissions reductions include Climate Change Agreements and financial incentives for energy efficiency technologies such as Combined Heat and Power; the Department is also working collaboratively with eight energy intensive sectors through the 2050 Industrial Roadmaps Programme on actions needed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and increase energy efficiency, whilst improving competitiveness. In addition, the Government is looking ahead to our emissions reduction plan which will set out how the UK will reduce its emissions through the 2020s across all sectors.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:09:52.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670355/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670355/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670355/answer/previousversion/29602","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to help carbon-intensive industries to reduce emissions.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","59094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670356","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs always investigate where they believe an employer is not paying the legal minimum wage, which includes following up every worker complaint they receive.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available figures show that HMRC identified almost £10.3m of arrears owed to over 58,000 workers in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2016 the Government doubled the National Minimum Wage penalty paid by employers from 100% to 200% of the arrears owed to the worker, up to a maximum of £20,000 per worker.</p><p> </p><p>We have also increased HMRC’s enforcement budget from £13m in 2015/16 to £20m in 2016/17, and my Right Honourable friend the Chancellor announced a further £4.3m investment in the 2016 Autumn Statement. This additional funding has enabled an increase in the number of compliance officers available to investigate minimum wage abuses and allowed HMRC to conduct more proactive, risk-based enforcement in sectors where there is a higher risk of workers not being paid the legal minimum wage.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-12T11:17:08.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670356/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670356/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent steps the Government has taken against employers for not paying the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","59056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670357","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Departments are currently doing some analysis with the Department for Exiting the European Union to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on businesses, consumers and other economic actors. Due to the decisions this Government has taken, the British economy is fundamentally strong and we are well-positioned to negotiate our departure from the EU. Employment is at a record high. There are over two million more people in employment compared with 2010 and around 900,000 fewer unemployed.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T11:49:54.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670357/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670357/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on UK jobs of the UK leaving the Single Market in the five years (a) before and (b) after that action is taken.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670359","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>All liability partnerships (LLPs) have a legal requirement to file annual accounts and Confirmation Statements with the Registrar each and every year. Failure to do so is a criminal offence and Companies House has a proactive system in place. This includes reminders being issued prior the deadline dates and, if they are not filed, there is a compliance process that reminds them of their obligations and the consequences of failing to file. If it is deemed to be in the public interest Companies House will take prosecution action against the LLP and its designated members.</p><p>For all other information legally required to be filed, on receipt of a public complaint, Companies House will consider what action to take. Companies House’s primary aim will be to try to achieve compliance. If the company does not comply, the case will be referred to prosecutors and a prosecution will be brought if it is deemed to be in the public interest. In the event of a conviction the Court would impose the appropriate penalty.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T11:50:58.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670359/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670359/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps Companies House takes to ensure that all legally required Limited Liability Partnership filing information is provided.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","59180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670360","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-17","<p>From the data available fewer than 5 individuals have been identified as having ceased employment by the Department and its partner organisations in the last three years and subsequently re-employed by the Department on a temporary basis.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-17T10:37:43.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670360/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670360/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many members of staff who ceased to be employed by his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies in the last three years have subsequently been re-employed by his Department on a temporary basis or as a third-party contractor or consultant.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","59170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670361","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Companies House has the initial responsibility for ensuring Limited Liability Partnerships (LLP) comply with their responsibilities under section 18 of the Limited Liability Partnerships (Application of Companies Act 2006) Regulations 2009. Companies House will consider what action to take on receipt of a public complaint that an LLP has failed to meet its obligations under section 162(6) of the Companies Act 2006, as applied by section 18 of the 2009 Regulations. Companies House's primary aim will be to try to achieve compliance. If the LLP does not comply, the case will be referred to prosecutors and a prosecution will be brought if it is deemed to be in the public interest.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T11:51:31.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670361/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670361/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which UK government agency is responsible for ensuring that Limited Liability Partnership registrations comply with section 18 of the Limited Liability Partnerships (Application of Companies Act 2006) Regulations 2009.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","59132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670362","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>No sanctions have been applied to Limited Liability Partnership designated members that are offshore corporate members and did not supply the details specified in section 18 of the Limited Liability Partnerships (Application of Companies Act 2006) Regulations 2009 in each of the last three years, the latest period for which information is available. Companies House has not received any public complaints related to this. Were it to do so it would consider what action to take. Companies House's primary aim would be to try to achieve compliance. If the LLP did not comply, the case would be referred to prosecutors and a prosecution would be brought if it were deemed to be in the public interest. In the event of a conviction the Court would impose the appropriate penalty.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T11:53:10.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670362/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670362/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-09","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what sanctions have been applied against Limited Liability Partnership designated members that are offshore corporate members and did not supply the details specified in section 18 of the Limited Liability Partnerships (Application of Companies Act 2006) Regulations 2009 since the coming into force of those regulations.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","59133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670363","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Department for International Trade is committed to increasing exports of British food and drink, including beer. We offer a range of services and support for both new and experienced exporters and we work closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and industry bodies such as the British Beer and Pub Association to help British brewers in their export efforts.</p><p>We are developing export campaigns in high growth markets where there is potential for increasing sales of British beer and we continue to help British brewers enter those markets and expand internationally. For example, in November last year we organised the first ever UK Beer and Cider Pavilion at the Food and Hotel China trade show in Shanghai. Over 30 British brands were represented.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-17T17:34:47.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670363/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670363/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-09","Beer: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to increase British beer exports.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","59136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670365","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-17","<p>The Department for International Trade does not currently have a redeployment pool.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-17T16:19:42.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670365/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670365/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-09","Department for International Trade: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670366","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>Parliament will be involved in helping shape the UK's future as we leave the European Union. We will keep Parliament informed of the development of the schedules.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T14:28:36.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670366/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670366/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670366/answer/previousversion/29610","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-09","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to his written ministerial statement of 5 December 2016, Official Report, HCWS316, on the UK's commitments at the World Trade Organisation, what process he plans to adopt to secure parliamentary approval of the necessary draft schedules he is preparing.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","59071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670367","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working closely with the Home Office to consider the range of options as to how migration of EU nationals might work once we have left. We are assessing the pros and cons of each potential option, including how EU nationals might be treated compared to others under these options.</p><p><br>Our ambition is to create an immigration system that allows us to control numbers and encourage the brightest and the best to come to this country, as part of a stable and prosperous future with the EU and our European partners.</p><p><br><strong><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-12T15:44:44.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670367/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670367/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-09","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make it his policy in immigration negotiations with the EU that (a) there is no discrimination between applicants on the basis of their country of origin and (b) no preferential access is granted for citizens of EU member states.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","59100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670368","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-16","<p>As at the 11th January 2017 the Department for Exiting the European Union has no staff in the redeployment pool.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-16T11:08:38.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670368/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670368/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-09","Department for Exiting the European Union: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","59144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670369","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>As at the 11th January 2017 one official has resigned from the Department for Exiting the European Union. There continue to be movements of civil servants between other Government Departments and DExEU as recruitment remains ongoing.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-13T14:27:52.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670369/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670369/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-09","Department for Exiting the European Union: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many officials have resigned from his Department since it was established.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","59134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670370","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 and ensure a functioning statute book on the day we leave the EU. This Great Repeal Bill will end the authority of EU law and return power to the UK.<br> <br>The Bill will preserve EU-derived legislation, including applicable European Court of Justice (ECJ) case law where appropriate, as it applies in the UK on exit day. <br><br>The Government will set out the content of the Bill and its implications in due course.<br><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-01-12T15:48:29.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670370/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670370/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-09","Legal Profession: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of maintaining the provisions of the Lawyer Services Directive after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","59238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670818","Home Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>There are a number of options as to how EU migration might work once we have left the European Union. We are considering various options and it would be wrong to set out further positions at this stage.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-12T17:23:52.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670818/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-09","Immigration Controls: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Transport on the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on future levels of staffing of border checkpoints at UK airports.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","908121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671692","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-16","<p>We have set out a clear manifesto commitment in England to tackle aggressive parking enforcement and excessive parking charges, and we are taking steps to tackle rogue and unfair practices by private parking operators. This Government has put in place a range of measures to deal with aggressive activities of private parking companies, including the banning of wheel clamping and towing. We are considering further reform.</p><p>Off-street parking policy is however a devolved matter to Scotland, and as such accreditation is a matter for the Scottish Government. Therefore, I can only comment on the accredited trade associations with respect to England.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-16T17:09:38.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671692/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671692/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671692/answer/previousversion/29607","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-09","Parking: Trade Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will require private car parking firms to join an accredited trade association.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","908132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671971","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>We are deeply disappointed and frustrated that the union has insisted on this damaging and disruptive strike action, which will cause misery for thousands of people.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State regularly discusses this important issue with his Cabinet colleagues. This Government is doing everything it can to limit the impact of this strike on passengers, and continues to consider all available options.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to closely monitor the situation to determine whether further action is necessary.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-12T12:35:22.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671971/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671971/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Southern: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on possible legislative steps to bring an end to the Southern Rail industrial action.","false","Biography information for Huw Merriman","Bexhill and Battle","Huw Merriman","908139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671972","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>We are currently gathering and analysing evidence to inform the second Road Investment Strategy, which will determine investment in the strategic road network beyond 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Core elements of this work are the six strategic studies, five of which were published last November, and Highways England’s 18 refreshed route strategies. This will be published in March.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-12T14:16:34.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671972/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671972/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department is making on formulating the second Roads Investment Strategy.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","908135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671973","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>It is critical that train companies and Network Rail work effectively together to deliver the standard of service that passengers expect. The new South Eastern and East Midlands franchises will be run with much closer alignment between infrastructure and train services. We will continue to develop our approach as further franchises are renewed.</p><p><em> </em></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-12T11:54:16.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671973/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671973/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Railways: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve co-ordination on track renewal and train operations on the railways.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","908136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671974","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Department’s road condition statistics highlight that local classified roads are improving, with fewer requiring maintenance. The Government is providing local highway authorities with over £6 billion between 2015 and 2021 for highways maintenance. We will soon be announcing how we will allocate a further £185 million for 2017/18 financial year, in addition to over £1 billion already committed, to improve the condition of local roads.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-12T15:12:42.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671974/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671974/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve the condition of local roads.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","908133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671975","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-12","<p>We want to bring new skills into the challenge of upgrading our railways and welcome opportunities for private sector involvement in rail infrastructure projects. We also continue to develop the model for greater alignment of track and train as further franchises are renewed, including the option of joint ventures.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-12T12:27:57.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671975/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671975/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-09","Railways: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he is making on his plans for increased private sector involvement in rail infrastructure projects.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","908137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668846","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>This Government is committed to creating a secure and clear democracy that works for all. We published our response to the Rt. Hon. Sir Eric Pickles’ report on electoral fraud in December 2016 setting out the Government’s approach to tackling the recommendations Sir Eric made.</p><p>The Electoral Commission publishes an annual analysis of electoral fraud on their website. (<a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/electoral-fraud/data-and-analysis" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/electoral-fraud/data-and-analysis</a>?)</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","58796","2017-01-12T08:17:49.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668846/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668846/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Election Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many convictions there have been for offences under electoral law in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668847","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>This Government is committed to creating a secure and clear democracy that works for all. We published our response to the Rt. Hon. Sir Eric Pickles’ report on electoral fraud in December 2016 setting out the Government’s approach to tackling the recommendations Sir Eric made.</p><p>The Electoral Commission publishes an annual analysis of electoral fraud on their website. (<a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/electoral-fraud/data-and-analysis" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/electoral-fraud/data-and-analysis</a>?)</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","58795","2017-01-12T08:17:49.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668847/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668847/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Election Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many electoral law offences have been committed by (a) voters and (b) political candidates or their agents in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668848","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government published its response to Sir Eric Pickles’ review of electoral fraud in December, and is now looking closely at how and when the work on each of the recommendations addressed in the response can be taken forward. In the coming weeks and months, the Government will work closely with the Electoral Commission, the Association of Electoral Administrators, the Society of Local Authority Chief Executives, and other electoral administrators, in order to set out clearly the nature and timing of that work. We will look to implement the majority of Sir Eric’s recommendations either through primary and secondary legislation, or through new or reinforced guidance, as appropriate. In its response, the Government has clearly identified where the recommendations that it intends to bring forward will require primary legislation in order to be implemented.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","58804","2017-01-10T13:25:30.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668848/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668848/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many of the 50 recommendations made in Securing the Ballot the Government plans to see implemented by (a) the Government or (b) other parties, including the Electoral Commission and returning officers, in time for (i) local authority elections in 2017, (ii) local authority elections in 2018, (iii) the next general election due in 2020 and (iv) elections of police and crime commissioners in 2020.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","58805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668849","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government published its response to Sir Eric Pickles’ review of electoral fraud in December, and is now looking closely at how and when the work on each of the recommendations addressed in the response can be taken forward. In the coming weeks and months, the Government will work closely with the Electoral Commission, the Association of Electoral Administrators, the Society of Local Authority Chief Executives, and other electoral administrators, in order to set out clearly the nature and timing of that work. We will look to implement the majority of Sir Eric’s recommendations either through primary and secondary legislation, or through new or reinforced guidance, as appropriate. In its response, the Government has clearly identified where the recommendations that it intends to bring forward will require primary legislation in order to be implemented.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","58805","2017-01-10T13:25:30.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668849/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668849/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many of the recommendations made in Securing the Ballot that the Government identifies in its response to that report as requiring or likely to require primary legislation the Government plans to implement in the (a) current Parliamentary session and (b) remainder of the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","58804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668850","Scotland Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>Government Ministers from a range of Departments make regular visits throughout the United Kingdom, including in Scotland. Details of meetings with external organisations are published in quarterly returns which are available at gov.uk.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-01-11T13:18:29.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668850/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668850/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-06","Official Visits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many official visits Government Ministers have made to Scotland in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","58868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668851","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>The 2015 Annual Report was published on 3 January and includes analysis of the socio-economic status of recruits to the Fast Stream between 2011, when monitoring of the socio-economic background of recruits to the Fast Stream began, and 2015. Analysis of the socio-economic status of recruits to the 2016-17 Fast Stream recruitment round will be published in the 2016 Annual Report later this year.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-11T08:41:48.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668851/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668851/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on what date the annual civil service report into socio-economic data for fast-stream recruits will be published.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","58908"
